It was supposed to be the drinks break but Clarke decided that 329 is more than enough for him, 150 for Hussey and a massive lead of 468. A selfless decision by Clarke, considering that he was 71 away from the world record score (Lara) and 51 away from an Australian Test record (Hayden). He must be quite knackered himself.

Clarke and gang took advantage of a deflated Indian outfit who were probably waiting for the declaration for an eternity now. India have close to two and a half days to bat out.

Tweet from Rajneesh Gupta: "First time in Test history that a side has posted two 250+ partnerships in the same innings."

Sanju: "Ashwin falls just 5 runs short of beating Agarkar's "record" of 161 runs without a wicket in Australia."

Qasim: "Looks like Clarke paid tribute to big man Inzi by not surpassing his 329."

12.30pm: Clarke's triple will have to wait a bit. Save for a couple of deliveries that squared him up outside off by Ishant, and a outside edge past slip which didn't carry, he's looked in supreme touch. The triple will be thoroughly deserved.

It was one of the better sessions for India, thought they didn't pick a wicket. There was more discipline in the bowling, less deliveries on the pads and more outside off. Could have been better had there been more attacking field sets. That's something entirely in Dhoni's hands it seems. I wonder whether the other seniors are assisting him enough. It's easy to make assumptions.

Unless there's a change of luck for India post lunch, milestones will continue to tumble. Join us at 1.10 pm.

10.28: The Indians walk out and shake Glenn McGrath's hand on the way out. Each hand over pink autographed caps to McGrath. Zaheer Khan rushes down the steps and hands over his cap. One fast bowler keeps another waiting... This is in support of the Jane McGrath Foundation. Plenty of pink around the stadium.

10.10am local: Good day to everyone and welcome to the coverage of the third day at the SCG. Weather update first up - seems pretty clear. Apparently it was a bit overcast a while back, just like it was for quite a while yesterday with the lights on. The experts reckon it's going to continue to be a good batting wicket. Therefore, it's India's day to lose.

Mark Kidger writes: "Just about the only interest left in this match is the timing of the declaration. With three full days left Australia could bat until past tea and try to get 500 ahead: the sort of score that would ensure that they will only bat once in the match and gives India no realistic prospect of saving the game."

That sums up Australia's plans. They've scored so quickly and if they continue, they might force a declaration well before tea. If you're an Indian supporter, you would hope that the top order was making mental notes watching Clarke and Ponting bat on this pitch. Seemed like they were batting on a different surface.

To reflect on Ponting, do read Sambit Bal's piece from yesterday. For the Indian angle, read Sidharth Monga's take on India having to do overtime in the field more often than not in the last year or so.

The best thing India have done is bowl their overs on time. There are positives even in the worst of days, as Dhoni would say.

Today was all about Ponting and Clarke. Ponting answered his doubters in the best manner, compiling a largely chanceless century. He barely gave the Indians a chance and earned every run. Clarke too was unfazed, treating seam and spin effortlessly. The Indians kept feeding the pair full deliveries on the pads, and few pitched up outside off - the kind that fetched Pattinson and Friends all the wickets. Two days into the Test and the gulf between the teams has widened.

There's plenty of analysis coming up from our team of writers. You might also want to check this out: our sister site, ESPN.co.uk, have some shiny Samsung phones and tablets to give away. All you have to do is decide whether a certain cricket team can be considered the greatest across any sport...

Thanks for your company today. Lot of mails from disappointed Indian fans. I empathise. Do join us tomorrow. Cheers!
